---
const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Why run locally instead of in the cloud?',
    answer: `<p>If you're trading frequently, you're probably already running your broker's desktop client for the speed and depth that web platforms can't match. Glasshouse picks up where those terminals leave off.</p>
<p>Persistent automation, your own logic, your research notes, your market data — none of it leaves your machine. Connect any local or remote AI model directly into the decision layer: analyse price action, surface signals, draft a thesis. When a condition is met, the loop is tight — no round trip to a cloud server, no shared infrastructure. Data in, logic runs, order out.</p>`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I use it alongside my existing tools?',
    answer: `
        <p>Glasshouse doesn't replace your trading tool stack — it is the bridge between research and live markets. Pick and choose what you need. Streaming price feeds and broker control are hard to implement and a headache to maintain — Glasshouse does the heavy lifting.</p>
        <p>Backtesting is deliberately out of scope — best left to specialised tools that can handle the computational infrastructure for historical simulation. Refine your strategy there, then deploy with Glasshouse when you're ready to go live.</p>
        `,
  },
  {
    question: 'Do I need to know a programming language to develop a trading strategy?',
    answer: `<p>You can if you want full deterministic control, but it is not necessary. Glasshouse exposes connectors to let an LLM drive your trading actions, so you can define a strategy in plain English using markdown rather than writing code.</p>
        <p>You can build a logical workflow by chaining conditions such as <code>abort if the S&amp;P 500 is below its 500-day SMA</code>, or actions such as <code>enter with a mid size bet using volatility targeting</code>. The LLM runs on your chosen schedule and follows your instructions.</p>
        <p>Most brokers provide a paper trading environment, so you can test everything before committing real capital.</p>
        <p>Note that LLM token usage fees apply on each run, so this approach is best suited to lower-frequency strategies. For higher-frequency execution, a local open-source model or a coded strategy is usually the better fit.</p>`,
},
  {
    question: "Aren't there already platforms that do this?",
    answer: `<p>None of them combine local-first infrastructure, real-time orchestration, risk enforcement, and the ability to run both autonomous agents and discretionary positions from one system. Most force you to pick a lane — quant or manual, cloud or local, broker-dependent or DIY.</p>
<p>Glasshouse is designed to grow with you. Start with smart triggers and manual trade plans, and move into fully automated agents as your confidence and skills develop. No one starts as a quant — and you shouldn't need to become one to manage your investment bets.</p>
<p>Even systematic investors feel the urge to make discretionary bets. Jim Simons, while building one of history's most successful quantitative funds, overrode his own models to buy gold on instinct and lost money. Glasshouse lets you run systematic and discretionary approaches side by side, with automated guardrails to limit downside.</p>
<p>Here are the closest alternatives:</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Platform</th>
      <th>Limitation</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>QuantConnect</td>
      <td> Pay per live node — one algorithm per server — with no shared state between them. No discretionary workflow, no built-in risk engine. Steep learning curve.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Alpaca</td>
      <td>Broker with an API — your capital is locked with them. No orchestration, no signals, no risk layer. You build everything else.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>TradingView</td>
      <td>Great charts and technical indicators, but no execution, no position management, no automation beyond alerts and unsecure webhooks. Glasshouse uses Lightweight Charts for the interface, but adds a full execution and risk layer on top.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Composer</td>
      <td>No-code, if-this-then-that allocation logic. Executes orders once a day only, meaning no downside protection when markets move swiftly against you. Holds your capital via Alpaca. US equities only.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>QuantRocket</td>
      <td>Local and Python — closest philosophically. But narrower: backtesting-focused, no real-time orchestration, no risk engine, no agent framework.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>OpenBB</td>
      <td>Excellent open-source research and data aggregation — essentially a free Bloomberg alternative. But analysis only: no execution, no broker integration, no position management, no risk controls, no trade automation.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Why does this exist?',
    answer: `<p>I spent nearly two decades working in the financial software industry. Ironically, I was terrible at managing my own finances and investments. Based in Sydney, I was setting alarms for overnight sessions, using disconnected tools, mentally drained by the continuous decision loop — buy more, sell, or do nothing. I needed a system that could watch my positions while I slept and take the weight off while I was awake. Nothing out there brought it all together in an accessible way.</p>
<p>Sadly, AI coding assistants weren't a thing when I started. Every piece of Glasshouse's core architecture has been carefully handcrafted. In fairness, I don't think you can vibe code a reliable real-time, event-driven asynchronous platform on top of socket-based broker APIs designed in the 90s.
</p>
<p>By the time the platform matured, local AI models became viable on a single machine, and frontier models could leverage tools through MCP connectors — exactly the kind of infrastructure Glasshouse was already built to support. What started as a personal tool evolved into a fully fledged platform.</p>`,
  },
];
---

<section id="faq" class="px-6 py-24">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
    <h2 class="text-center text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-text-primary sm:text-4xl">
      Frequently Asked Questions
    </h2>

    <div class="mt-12 space-y-4">
      {faqs.map((faq) => (
        <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-card">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-text-primary [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
            <span class="font-medium">{faq.question}</span>
            <svg
              class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-text-muted transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
              fill="none"
              stroke="currentColor"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
            >
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4" />
            </svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer px-6 pb-6" set:html={faq.answer} />
        </details>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .faq-answer :global(p) {
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
  }

  .faq-answer :global(p:first-child) {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .faq-answer :global(code) {
    padding: 0.15rem 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
    font-size: 0.9em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .faq-answer :global(table) {
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.625;
  }

  .faq-answer :global(thead) {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .faq-answer :global(th) {
    padding: 0.625rem 1rem;
    text-align: left;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text-primary);
  }

  .faq-answer :global(td) {
    padding: 0.625rem 1rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    vertical-align: top;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .faq-answer :global(td:first-child) {
    white-space: nowrap;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-text-primary);
  }
</style>
